===Definitions===
{{head|zh|hanzi}}

# {{lb|zh|Chinese mythology}} the [[w:Kui (Chinese mythology)|Kui]], a mythological one-legged creature or spirit, variously described as a dragon-like mountain spirit, a wood-and-stone demon, or a sea beast
#* {{zh-x|жңЁзҹі д№Ӣ жҖӘ жӣ° еӨ”гҖҒиқ„иңҪгҖӮ|Monsters of wood and stone are called '''Kui''' and Wangliang.|ref=Guoyu, вҖңLu yu xiaвҖқ|CL}}
#* {{zh-x|еұұ жңү еӨ”пјҢйҮҺ жңү еҪ·еҫЁпјҢжҫӨ жңү е§”иӣҮгҖӮ|Mountains have the '''Kui''', fields have the Fanghuang, and marshes have the Weiyi.|ref=Zhuangzi, вҖңDashengвҖқ|CL}}
#* {{zh-x|е…¶ дёҠ жңү зҚёпјҢзӢҖ еҰӮ зүӣпјҢи’ј иә« иҖҢ з„Ў и§’пјҢдёҖ и¶іпјҢеҮәе…Ҙ ж°ҙ еүҮ еҝ… йўЁйӣЁпјҢе…¶ е…ү еҰӮ ж—ҘжңҲпјҢе…¶ иҒІ еҰӮ йӣ·пјҢе…¶ еҗҚ жӣ° еӨ”гҖӮ|On it there is a beast, shaped like an ox, with a dark-blue body and no horns, one-legged; whenever it enters or leaves the water there must be wind and rain, its light is like the sun and moon, its sound is like thunder, and its name is '''Kui'''.|ref=Shanhaijing, вҖңDahuang dong jingвҖқ|CL}}
# {{lb|zh|rare}} a wild ox; a large wild bovine; also written {{zh-l|зҠӘ}} or compared with {{zh-l|зҠ©}}
#* {{zh-x|е…¶ зҚё еӨҡ зҠҖ иұЎпјҢеӨҡ еӨ”зүӣгҖӮ|Its beasts include many rhinoceroses and elephants, and many '''kui-oxen'''.|ref=Shanhaijing, вҖңZhongshan jingвҖқ|CL}}
# Kui, a legendary music minister under {{w|Emperor Shun}}
#* {{zh-x|еёқ жӣ°пјҡгҖҢеӨ”пјҢе‘Ҫ жұқ е…ё жЁӮпјҢж•ҷ иғ„еӯҗгҖӮгҖҚ|The emperor said: вҖң'''Kui''', I appoint you to take charge of music and teach the sons of nobles.вҖқ|ref=Shujing, вҖңShundianвҖқ|CL}}
#* {{zh-x|жҳ”иҖ…пјҢиҲң дҪң дә”ејҰ д№Ӣ зҗҙпјҢд»Ҙ жӯҢ еҚ—йўЁпјӣеӨ” е§Ӣ еҲ¶ жЁӮпјҢд»Ҙ иіһ и«ёдҫҜгҖӮ|In ancient times, Shun made a five-stringed qin to sing the вҖңSouth WindвҖқ; '''Kui''' first established music in order to reward the feudal lords.|ref=Liji, вҖңYuejiвҖқ|CL}}
# {{lb|zh|historical}} Kui, an ancient state in present-day Zigui County, Hubei, destroyed by Chu in 634 BCE; also called {{zh-l|йҡ—еңӢ}} or {{zh-l|жӯёеңӢ}}
#* {{zh-x|з§ӢпјҢжҘҡдәә ж»… еӨ”пјҢд»Ҙ еӨ”еӯҗ жӯёгҖӮ|In autumn, the people of Chu destroyed '''Kui''' and returned with the viscount of Kui.|ref=Zuozhuan, Duke Xi, 26th year|CL}}
# {{lb|zh|historical}} Kui Prefecture, a historical prefecture centered around present-day Fengjie, Chongqing
#* {{zh-x|зҷҪеёқ еӨ”е·һ еҗ„ з•° еҹҺпјҢиңҖжұҹ жҘҡеіҪ ж·· ж®Ҡ еҗҚгҖӮ|Baidi and '''Kui Prefecture''' are separate cities; the Shu River and Chu Gorges have mixed and differing names.|ref=Du Fu, вҖңKuizhou ge shi juejuвҖқ|CL}}
# {{lb|zh|literary|rare}} reverent; respectful; standing respectfully
#* {{zh-x|йӣҒиЎҢ йҒҝ жҷҜпјҢеӨ”з«Ӣ иӣҮйҖІпјҢиҖҢ еҫҢ ж•ў йҖІгҖӮ|They moved aside in goose-like rows, stood reverently and advanced like snakes, and only then dared to go forward.|ref=Jia Yi, Xinshu, вҖңQuanxueвҖқ|CL}}
